replies.body:
Don't worry about learning everything immediately, LoL is a complicated game and it's only getting more complicated, with new champion releases every couple months, etc. The basics can be fairly straightforward to learn, especially if you have a background in similar games, but there is a massive amount of information to take in; the up-side is that, for the most part, once you get your fundamentals down, learning new champions and such becomes much easier. The important part is to have fun, it's a video game, afterall :)

One thing I would recommend, as Kindlejack has already mentioned, is to take advantage of the free champion rotation to try out every champion (except Yorick :P he was removed from the rotation since he has some underlying problems at the moment), and keep an open mind and try champions again, even if it's just loading up a custom game by yourself to test out the champion's abilities; there have been many cases where the first time I played a champion, I really didn't like them, but later on, especially as my skills improved, I really came to like them. Overall though, as far as what champions you *should* be playing, play the ones you like, honestly. Playing champions you actually enjoy playing will encourage you to improve at them, and help you learn the game in the process.

---------

#Information dump:

(I'm just leaving this all here for you to go at your own pace, don't feel pressured to learn all of this immediately; this is mostly just for reference or to give you a starting point. Like I said before, there is a lot of information in this game, honestly it took me a good year or so to feel like I had a decent knowledge of the game, though I was a bit stubborn about looking up information on the internet at first, so it probably won't take you as long)

(I also want to say up front that nothing in this game is dogma; you can pull off anything so long as you know what you're doing and are sufficiently skilled, though of course the game is designed to make some things easier than others. The following resources are a good starting point though, and can give some good guidance, but take them with a grain of salt and always use your brain to figure out *why* things are a certain way, etc.)

As far as resources, beyond Sir ArmaMalum's guide (and the guides within that one), 2ez.gg is a very helpful resource that basically aggregates a ton of popular LoL related sites and resources into one window/tab. Just some guidance on some my favorite sites;

* Surrender@20/ReignOfGaming are two popular news sites and also post information on PBE patches, which kind of give you a heads up on possible changes coming to the game (though I wouldn't worry too much about this when you're still learning the game);
* op.gg and LoLKing have a lot of useful statistics and information, as well as histories of your personal games if you want to go back and look at your statistics (and you can also use the Match History tool that Riot provides; each one provides slightly different information);
* ProBuilds is a great site that pulls information from professional player's games so you can learn what items/runes/masteries they're building and how they use their skill points, etc. it's a good place to start if you're trying to learn a new champion (also watching youtube videos of those players/champions);
* ChampionSelect.net and Champion.gg both give good stats on champions and can give some guidance on how champions interact;
* and last but not least, LoLWiki will be your best friend.

Watching streams and VoD's (video on demand) on twitch/youtube or other sites (ie. azubu, etc) can be very helpful, often more than just playing a bunch of games, since you're often learning from the experience of a more experienced player. Two of my favorites are:

* Nightblue3: He's a high ranked jungler (it's likely that jungling isn't something you'll see a whole lot of until lvl 30), but his stream is largely devoted to teaching how to play jungle, which I think can help give a broader perspective of the game even if you don't play jungle
* ls: He's currently the head coach of Gravity, a professional team. He's someone who really understands the game, his youtube coaching videos (his youtube username is lastshadow9) really opened my mind to how the game really works. Bear in mind that his coaching style can be a bit aggressive, and that he tends to dump a ton of information into his videos, so it can be a bit much to take in all at once, but the concepts that he discusses are incredibly valuable when learning to play.

Good luck, and remember to have fun! (and you can feel free to add me in game if you want, though I'm not on too often these days...)

